description.narrative:
The project&rsquo;s overall goal is to promote accountability using the Constitution as a tool for the observance of human rights and the active participation of citizens in national affairs through&nbsp;a sustained dialogue for change (advocacy) and engagement with duty bearers. The project&rsquo;s immediate objectives:1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To enhance public knowledge of the Constitution and human rights. 2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To enhance strategic engagements with constitutional commissions and state institutions responsible for human rights promotion and elections.3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; To support and enhance the ability of Human Rights Defenders (HRDs) to assert and defend the constitutional rights of individuals and groups in Zimbabwe. The main Problem is lack of constitutional and election process awareness among citizens leading to abuse of citizens' rights by government. Government has failed&nbsp;facilitate for&nbsp;awareness of the constitution to the citizens, there is lack of promotion and protection of civil rights&nbsp; and lack of democratic culture in Zimbabwe leading to repression of citizens rights. Rights holders for this project mainly include women and youth in selected&nbsp; districts Matebeleland South, North and Masvingo&nbsp; Provinces. These youths and women will use the&nbsp;Constitutional &nbsp;provisions in the Bill of Rights to demand accountability from duty bearers and their right to &nbsp;participation in the just and peacefull elections of 2018. This project main falls within the Democracy Intervention area ( strengthening democratic culture&nbsp;objective) in the current Diakonia Zimbabwe's Strategic Plan for 2016 - 2020. It will be implemented&nbsp;by Zimbabwe Council of Churches in selected district in Matebeleland South and North&nbsp;and Masvingo Provinces and advocacy work will implemented at a national level.&nbsp;
